< name>
Michael Teoli</name>
< time>
1535385035568</time>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
This is the second of two Nature Centers on the historic Angels Crest Highway that runs from La Canada to Wrightwood. I highly recommend visiting both the Chilao Visitor Center and this one, Grassy Hollow Visitor Center. They have some cool taxidermy and other fun things for kids. They have a push button opposites video series about different animals and lift the flap wall information that is easy to miss as it blends into a mural. They have a binocular station on the deck where you can do some amazing bird watching!!!

They also have a bunch of free Smoky Bear swag! We even got a frisbee! Both these nature centers provided a ton of fun for our family! Great stop!< /review>

<Name>Panya Baldia< /Name>< Date>
1621625836815</Date>
<rate>1< /rate>< review>
Like many other reviewers here, if I could give Carbon Health negative stars I would. The organization is simply incompetent when it comes to billing. I went as a walk-in for a simple rash and was told that my insurance would cover the cost. The consultation took 5 minutes maximum where the practitioner just prescribed a steroid cream and sent me on my merry way.

Fast forward a month later and I get a charge for $575, out which I am forced to pay 200 dollars out of pocket. I was not informed that a consultation for a simple rash would lead to a $575 dollar charge to my insurance. When I called the billing company, I was told that since I was coded as a "new patient" my bill arbitrarily would be a whopping $575, regardless of what the treatment actually was. Absolutely absurd. Do yourself a favor and do not go to this money making machine.</review>

<review>Would you like your skin infection to be wildly misdiagnosed as a virus rather than a simple bacterial infection, without any microbial culturing to validate?

I was prescribed a potent inflammatory cream, which turned a painless lesion into something so uncomfortable I could only sleep on my back. I was also told to use it for 16 weeks (4 months!) even after writing to express concern that symptoms were worsening.

After more than 8 weeks of pain and life wasted, and the infection spreading, I decided to get a second opinion elsewhere, where a thorough culturing of the site indicated a bacterial infection. I was completely cured and back to normal in about 4-5 days with a common oral antibiotic.

Additionally, I was told the use of the inflammatory cream prescribed by Carbon Health was inappropriate without a careful diagnosis and that it is problematic when applied in a skin crevice such as where my lesion occurred.

I wish I could have 2 months of my life returned to me. Can you imagine having an improperly diagnosed infection spreading and being told by Carbon Health to continue the same course for 16 weeks and not suggesting any follow-up? Patients: please, stay clear of this clinic!

< review>
This is the only Urgent Care my Medicare HMO Imperial  Health of Calif. allows.  On Oct 20 I slipped in a sandal, heard a crack, knew it wasn't good and limped home. Did RICE (Rest,Ice,Compression,Elevation) Next morning went to Carbon because my HMO will pay and it is a one stop shop with XRays on premise.  I was surprized when the NP told me the XRay showed it was not broken. Just said stay off as much as possible.  On Oct 23 I went to my Podiatrist Dr Meoldy Chong who ordered the XRays from Carbon.  That took another 4 days with my perseverance. Dr Chong told me Carbon's XRays were blurry and unreadable and prescribed new ones.  On Oct 30, after 9 days I found out the truth.  Not only was my foot broken, it was the most severe fracture you can have, called a Jones Fracture where 15-20% of cases do not heal and if I had been a professional athlete would require surgery. How can Carbon be so incompetent?  In March I was positive I  had Covid 19, and they wouldn't test me, said my symptoms  didn't warrant it.  They let me walk out to infect other people thinking I just had a cold.  A week after other friends tests came back positive they admitted they were wrong. < review>
Before I went to the medical office I was impressed. As a first time patient at carbon, the app was great. The bot in the app asked all the intake questions the receptionist and dr would initially asked. I even snapped a photo of the affected area on my leg. I aited about 5 minutes before being seen by the doctor. The waiting room was modern, and the rest of the facility was clean. After leaving, the app reminded me when to take the medication. Very impressive.</review>

< gmap_id>
0x808f7e1fd6491fad:0x5f41918b5641488c<//gmap_id>
<Date>1572722356517</Date>< text>
I think Carbon Health is fine to go to if you're in a jam and need medical care, but I have visited twice for urgent care and am not a fan.

Treatment: I came in for an infection and was prescribed antibiotics. The office did not do a culture, and it turned out that the antibiotics prescribed were not effective against whatever bacterial strain I had, so I ended up having to go to the ER in the middle of the night a week later. The doctors at the ER thought it was unusual for the urgent care office to not have done a culture to make sure that I was on appropriate medication.

Bedside manner: Both times I came to this office, I thought the PAs I spoke to were quite dismissive, and the first one seemed to not believe my symptoms until they were confirmed by tests. I was in a lot of pain at the time, so this was pretty upsetting.

Payment: I paid a low co-pay at my first visit and was told there would be no co-pay for my second visit. About a month later, I received additional bills for both visits.

On the flip side, the office is comfortable, the support staff was nice, and the app works pretty well. It was also easy to make an appointment on my phone. YMMV.< /text>

< Text>
I'm by no means a serious runner, but I run a couple times a week.  Unfortunately, my running activities gave me a bit of an infected nail bed on my toe. It was super painful and made walking difficult, so I made an appointment online at Direct Urgent Care after hearing about them from a friend.  They took my information and had an appointment available later that day.  Totally blown away from the prompt and thorough medical attention.  They even followed up with me through the app two days later to make sure I was on the mend and feeling better.  Sure hope I don't get injured again in the near future - but if I do, I will certainly book an appointment at Direct Urgent Care again.</Text>

< review>
Ark Animal Hospital has got to be the BEST veterinary facility in San Diego!! The staff is superb and we just LOVE LOVE LOVE Dr. Chu. She is an excellent veterinarian. THIS FACILITY IS PRIVATELY OWNED AND NOT AFFILIATED WITH OTHER PLACES WITH THE SAME NAME! Everyone is very knowledgeable about animals! Their prices are extremely reasonable, too! We have gone to many vets here in the San Diego area but when we happened across Ark Animal Hospital we made this place our go-to for everything for our cats! We have been customers now since 2005. Since that time we have had to euthanize two cats (one in 2010 and one in 2014) They took great care of both fur babies and handled the very painful experience so professionally! When it was time to acquire a new kitten, they were amazing with her and we continue to bring Lily in for her yearly exams. she feels very comfortable with the staff and gets cool kitty treats!! We are very satisfied with Ark Animal Hospital and we highly recommend them! (This review is also in yelp)<//review>

< review>
Our dogs have been cared for by the WONDERFUL staff at Ark for over 16 years. Everyone there is caring and knowledgeable and goes above and beyond to be sure that our fluffies receive the best possible care.  The hours are great, the cost reasonable, lots of parking, excellent facilities.  I especially appreciate the follow up calls after one of the dogs has been sick or had a procedure to see how he is doing. Another thing none of our friends seem to have at their dogs' vets is an after-hours number to leave a message where the vet will call back and offer advice - that's been a wonderful benefit too.  We love Ark and they love our boys - and our boys love the staff (just not shots!) :)<//review>

< review>
I was visiting my Mom and my warning light came on telling me to check my tires pressure. The tire store had just closed so they told me to go down the street to this station. There was a nice kid that checked and filled all my tires and didn't charge me anything. Come to find out, it is my mother's favorite station. She is elderly and they come out and pump her gas for her so she doesn't even have to get out of the car. They deserve your patronage.</review>

< Text>
Beautiful apartments and staff that work with you. If you're willing to communicate with them and voice any concerns, they'll help you out.

If you're looking to move in then I recommend the following these guidelines for the best experience:
- Keep following up with them during the application process so you know what to do next, you're not done until you sign the 64 page lease (mostly informational, my group lawyer read the whole thing) and go in to get your parking permits (you need a permit for every vehicle even if not in the covered spot) and keys (apartment keys, mail keys, and pool key).
- When it comes time for move in inspection: go through with a fine toothed comb. You should bring your own paper to write down anything you notice and then transfer it to their sheet. Their sheet has small boxes so I put most things in the comments. I also had my own checklist which is also a good idea.
- Get set up with the RentCafe app. You can set up other residents, but you MUST set up the primary first. You have to ensure the name, email, phone number, and T-code all match. I was consistently making a typo with my wife's phone number and it wouldn't let me in. Once you're set up, get autopay rolling. It's convenient and avoids late fees, no need for checks.
- Submit new work orders for the most important things you found while doing the move-in inspection. This allows you to keep track of the issues you care most about.< /Text>

Loved my apartment and amenities. My wife at the time was 9 months pregnant with our second child and due any day but with the help of family we packed up and moved out within a couple of weeks. We returned the keys were told if the apartment was in proper condition we would receive some of our deposit. My wife’s mother cleaned the apartment and we knew the carpet would need replacing of course but for the most part it was cleaner than when we moved in. About two weeks after we moved we received a bill for about $5000 stating cleaning fees and early lease termination. I went to the office to find out what happened since I was told that if I hurried and moved I would be avoiding these fees. I was basically met by a whole different management team and told that prior management had been fired and the agreement the prior management had given us was unable to be honored because they did a lot of things they were not permitted to do. We have been here 4 years and it has gotten worse every year. Thing only thing that good about this place is the location - their only saving grace.

The apartment being "gated" is a joke & does nothing as I always see cars with wheels stolen, homeless people walking around and dumpster diving,  sketchy looking people who probably don't live here walking around all hours of the day. The security they have a night is also a joke. We haven't had anything major happen except had a set of hubcaps stolen once and a car cover stolen twice in our 4 years here. Thank goodness.

There's also never parking for residents because they don't enforce parking permits for permit marked spots. Half of the time you're probably parking on the street. The street typically has a few cars that have been abandoned - you can tell by all of the cobwebs on the tires of the car. Also, you can  periodically expect to find someone's window shattered on the street.

The maintenance requests here are a scam. I have requested repairs for mold, water intrusion and much more in the past. Sometimes they take a couple of weeks to reach out and other times they mark a project was completed when no one ever came out here to check our apartment out or if they did there was never any communication about it. So whatever issues come up - expect to deal with it for longer than you should.

There are always different faces at the office and they always have an attitude. As far as I'm concerned - the fact that we're even paying for this over priced shoebox is the fact that they even have a job so show some damn respect. You have to go in to get anything done because they don't answer the phone most of the time.

Paying rent is a hassle as they charge a ridiculous fee to send a payment electronically so anyone who has a brain has to still use checks and walks it into the office like we're time traveling into the past. You would think they would make it easier to pay them their damn money.

The landscapers start at 7:30-45 waking up the whole freakin' complex. They do it slowly because they know they are not supposed to start until 8am. Absolutely ridiculous.

There are stray cats everywhere but don't worry they're fed by all of the rats running in the parking lot.

I feel in the last few years (especially since FPI started managing this complex) the service has gone downhill, crime in the apartment has gone up and the prices are skyrocketing with no perks at all (Sequoia, the previous management company, had perks for signing on for another year). <UserId.>114714540192669718999<//UserId.>< Name>
B. Li</Name>
<date>1564911993685</date><rating>3</rating>< review>
It's a very average restaurant plaza. However, it's location makes it incredibly convenient.

The 3 major spots in this plaza are Verde Cafe, Ajisen Ramen, and Sala Thai (in no particular order).

Verde has milk tea and some mixed cuisines for lunch (but they're also known for pre-making and microwaving them). Ajisen is known for ramen and their lunch combos. Sala Thai is the third in its franchise and is a pretty reliable spot for lunch combos.</review>

< Review>
This is by far my favorite Home Depot (probably even my favorite hardware / lumber store). The main pros and cons:

Pros:
1. Very good customer service: In general, there are enough store employees who can answer basic questions and in general you can easily get hold of experts for help / ideas. In particular, store manager Manny can help if you have additional questions.

2. Competitive pricing to meet online / other brick and mortar retailers, including lumber. As mentioned above the customer service and expert advice make this together my fav.

3. Truck / tool rental: I haven’t utilized their truck rental yet but it seems reasonably priced to me  I love their equipment rental for more involved projects for a heavy task or two.

4. A host of other small / big conveniences including clean restrooms, lines never too long, etc. So can make for a good project shopping few hours.

Cons: None really, some nice-to-haves.
1. A basic cafeteria / coffee store inside would be a nice plus. Although personally I wish it were 5 min rather than 15 min away for me! :)< /Review>

<Review>Thursday, July 30th 2020
After returning from the Home Depot, I discovered, in horror, that I had lost my wallet.
Backtracking, I returned to the Marina store.

< text>
You probably know what The Home Depot is, so why do that. You already get endless ads for it on the radio, streaming service (if you go cheap), etc.
This branch is ok. Doesn't always want all you are after, so check online before going.
Before the new shopping area and Whole Foods came along to Playa Vista, this was one of the most convenient public toilets you could use when in need.
Driving in LA can be annoying, long distances, traffic, and then you get that warning of an imminent pee/poop and you start hunting for the place to stop. This used to be one of those places for me.
Need a cheaper Christmas tree? This is a good place for it. Need to find some help hauling or moving you can find plenty of people offering those services in the parking area.
So, yup, a good place all around.<//text>

Either I used the Jedi mind trick or got some  customer service out of this world...  I bought a kitchen aid grill last year.. somehow I lost the tank connector. I come in and buy the only one they have... It doesn't fit. .. I come back and buy fittings.. it doesn't work.. finally I talk to returns and then everyone in the plumbing department.. I'm told I'll have to order the part from kitchen aid directly..
So Instead I walk back to the grill department and tell Jenn my problem.. she says "I don't know what we can do about that" I say "how about we get a wrench and take the one off this kitchen aid grill just like mine'
Minutes later after retreiving a wrench the correct connector was in my hand. I asked how can I exchange this? "You probably can't" she said,so without talking,  I handed her the one I bought the week before and she walked me to the exit.
Like I said I don't know if I used some Jedi mind trick or Jenn is just giving customer service out of this world.. either way, as someone who comes here Almost daily I'm very grateful. And with executive decisions like that,  Jenn needs a promotion and  to be employee of the month!!< /review>

<Review>This is one of the nicer Home Depots I have been to. Located in an upscale area, it's extremely easy to access from Jefferson Blvd which has 4 lanes in both directions. There is always ample parking with 3 exit/entrances. The store itself is always clean and organized. Employees are always friendly and helpful. It can get crowded like any Home Depot but normally it's not too bad and the checkout lines move quickly. They have a huge selection of plants in their garden section, definitely a one stop shopping experience for all your gardening needs.
This is a great place to shop for Christmas items during the holiday season, they have a large selection of lights, ornaments and other decor. Also probably the best place to find a Christmas tree for a great price. Their tree lot is huge, they have plenty of trees to choose from and the purchasing/loading process is usually quick.<//Review></record>

I've been here a couple of times and won't be going back. Both times, I came in looking for screws of a particular size. The first time, I spent 90 minutes searching for the correct size myself, as well as waiting for someone to show up to the department to help me. Twice, I asked for help, and both times, I was told someone would be right over to help. Neither time did anyone show up. Finally, I spoke to the manager, and he helped me himself. Today, the something similar happened. I spoke to a customer service rep, explained what had happened during the previous visit, and all he did was tell me what aisle to go to. I looked myself, found nothing, and approached another rep. I asked him if he would please cal someone to that department, but he said that he would help me himself. He asked what aisle and size he'd be right over. Of course, he never showed up, so I approached a cashier. She helped me look, but it was clear that this department was not something she was very familiar w/. I finally spoke to the manager, and he found someone to help me. Their customer service is really lacking, and for a store that's so large w/ so many options to choose from in areas that require a good deal of technical know-how, they should have people who are accountable enough to show up to designated areas to help customers in need, as well as being knowledgeable enough to do so. I really don't feel that's asking too much.</Text>

< review>
The service at this particular Home Depot is pretty uneven.  I've never been disappointed by the paint department.  Go off hours is you can to avoid crowds.  The nursery is pretty well stocked and have a decent variety throughout the year.  Prices on the basics, like soil and fertilizer are OK.  On the other hand, I've never had much luck find hardware or plumbing parts.  They seem to be consistently out stock of what would seem to be basic items like PVC elbows or #8 stainless bolts.  If you need to get a key cut, save your money and drive up the road to Advance Lock and Key, where you can get it done right for the same price.</review>

<text>Worst Customer Service. I ordered a Stackable Washer Dryer from Home Depot online in early February. When I bought the unit online, I was never prompted to order a stacking unit or the hoses necessary to complete the installation (which other companies do). I had to schedule two separate deliveries, once because of missing items required for the installation. The delivery times fill up quickly so there is a substantial lag time in between each. There is no centralized number that you can call and get assistance - the delivery company is separate from Home Depot, and Home Depot online customer support is separate from Home Depot in-store. Each department operates independently and won't provide assistance, or even connect you to the other department. Every time I've called this Home Depot store I'm on hold for about 10 minutes. 13 days ago I canceled my order and requested a refund (about $2500) and I have yet to see the refund in my account. I've been running up against the typical walls where no one is accountable and I can't get an updated on the status of my refund. < review>
I've been going to this store for many years, but seriously, I try not to. I only go when price is a real issue, and what they have will work. Not everything is less than a regular lumber yard, by the way. Moulding is not particularly well priced and given that you have to cut the lengths you want yourself, the moulding should cost less. The doors "off the shelf" need to be sighted for straightness, and the quality is inferior to domestic products like doors that come from TM Cobb. The cabinetry is a bad joke. I'm competitive with their brands, and I'm custom.

The things I find worth the aggravation of going there for is their prices on redwood, and especially fencing materials, and tools.

And then there is customer service. Just read the other reviews. I've been to other Home Depot's that do a much better job in that area. It's not like the problem is endemic to the chain. This store just sucks is all. So there you go...</review>

<UserId.>112498926205918484056</UserId.><Name>Nick Holt</Name>< Date>
1540572460762< /Date>
< rating>
1</rating>
< Text>
My experience with Home Depot staff in purchasing front doors and installation was poor. (However, the experience with the actual company contracted with Home Depot to complete the installation was excellent.)

In doing a good amount of research about cost of new front doors for our condo complex, our HOA visited Home Depot in Marina del Rey, Playa Vista.

In our meeting with Ben, in the doors and windows section of the store, I was verbally informed that we would receive a multi-door discount ("should be close to (around $276 for each door )." This quote was reasonable and came in under 2 other quotes we went with.

With this understanding in place, we agreed to move forward with the job. Ben asked me to return to the store to complete paperwork. Since it was the end of the day and Ben was about to leave for the day, I rushed to the store to pay. I walked with Ben and the contract to the register to complete the payment and quickly signed paperwork trusting Ben had reflected accurate pre-agreed upon information in the contract.

While the cashier was completing purchase, I reviewed the contract and noted that NOT ONLY did Ben NOT give us the multi-door discount -- full fee of $376/door, but NOW we were incurring an addition fee by the installer. This was a $1500+ difference. I, again immediately, raised the issue saying we might not be able to do the job, due to having a lower bid, and I was reassured by Ben that he would "make a note on the order ... don't worry."

I left the store, returned home and awaited follow up from the store. If I hadn't called, I'd still be waiting. Throughout this process, I NEVER received proactive follow up on the order and had to call numerous times with staff -- Ben and his Supervisor. They both sounded exhausted and almost irritated that they had to answer the phone and provide customer service.

Ben's Supervisor informed me that we would no longer receive a discount. According to Ben and his Supervisor, "Due to the doors being 1/2" wider we're not able to give you the discount now, " as well as "the installer is charging the additional fee so you'll have to pay both."

Did Ben not understand the initial feedback from the installer about the job? Did he not know that we were not eligible for the discount? Did he blatantly distort the truth with me? These do not seem like issues on my side of the table. Instead of acknowledging  Home Depot's errors and try to fix be there issue created, I was made to pay. At best, this experience seems incompetent. At worst, dubious business practices.

The Home Depot Supervisor said she would consult with her boss to see if she could get a $300 discount on the order.

After the hours of our investment and calls back and forth for this job, we reluctantly moved forward with the job and accepted the credit. However, in no way does the $300 credit compensate for the distortions, lack of quality customer service and time and effort we spent on this job.

This experience has changed the way I look at Home Depot. I do not recommend services provided at Home Depot, and encourage you to more grateful service providers.<//Text>

< review>
Wow.  On the outside this looks like any other Home Depot across the county, and we have personally been to many.   On the inside, however, it's a different story.  You have got to know exactly what you need to buy before you enter because you won't find anybody working there who is very knowledgeable, or is the least bit interested in serving the customer.  When we tried to pay for some items recently, we literally had to stand at the check stand for at least a minute or more while the cashier was in personal conversation with another employee.  They were apparently reliving the events of the previous evening as we stood patiently (perhaps impatiently) waiting for them to finish their social hour-break room conversation.  Annoyed by this type of behavior, we asked the cashier if we could speak to a manager.  The cashier pointed out that the manager was the women she was having the conversation with!

Way to go Home Depot!  Hire disrespectful, disinterested and thoughtless employees, and, as a reward, promote them to management.

It is true, the fish does rot from the head.<//review>

This Home Depot is the bourgeois do it yourself center.  You have more blue collar folks looking for a light bulb and shelving  than contractors. < review>
Great selection but lacking in customer service.  I'm a general contractor that uses HD all over the country. I gave this HD 4 stars because I liked the selection of products it has on the shelf.  The more selection in tools, lumber, hvac, electrical, plumbing, etc. it keeps me from having to run around town finding specialty parts. In saying that I did see a lack in customer service for the average weekend warrior DIYer.  I also want to point out the large tool selection with Milwaukee, Rigid, Bosch and so on.<//review>
